# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cleveland
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cleveland/1820-united-states-census] The **1820 United States census** was the fourth census conducted in the United States.
[src:cleveland/1820-united-states-census] The 1820 census included six new states: Louisiana, Indiana, Mississippi, Illinois, Alabama and Maine.
[src:cleveland/1820-united-states-census] There has been a district wide loss of 1820 census records for Arkansas Territory, Missouri Territory, and New Jersey.
[src:cleveland/1820-united-states-census] The total population was determined to be 9,638,453, of which 1,538,022 were slaves.
[src:cleveland/1820-united-states-census] The center of population was about 120 miles (193 km) west-northwest of Washington in Hardy County, Virginia (now in West Virginia).
[src:cleveland/1820-united-states-census] This was the first census in which any states recorded a population of over one million—New York, Virginia, and Pennsylvania—as well as the first in which a city recorded a population of over 100,000—New York.
[src:cleveland/1820-united-states-census] Also, in this census and the 14 subsequent ones, New York was the most populous state until being superseded by California in the 1970 census.
[src:cleveland/1820-united-states-census] The 1820 census contains a great deal more information than previous censuses.
[src:cleveland/1820-united-states-census] Several of these columns were for special counts, and not to be included in the aggregate total.
[src:cleveland/1820-united-states-census] Doing so would have resulted in counting some individuals twice.
[src:cleveland/1820-united-states-census] Census takers were asked to use double lines, red ink or some other method of distinguishing these columns so that double counting would not occur.
[src:cleveland/1820-united-states-census] For example, the count of free white males between 16 and 18 was a special count, because these individuals were also supposed to be tabulated in the column for free white males of age 16 and under 26.
[src:cleveland/1820-united-states-census] The other special counts were foreigners not naturalized, persons engaged in agriculture, persons engaged in commerce, and persons engaged in manufacture.
[src:cleveland/1820-united-states-census] Census takers were also instructed to count each individual in only one of the occupational columns.
[src:cleveland/1820-united-states-census] For example, if an individual was engaged in agriculture, commerce, and manufacture, the census taker had to judge which one the individual was primarily engaged in.
[src:cleveland/1820-united-states-census] Census taking was not yet an exact science.
[src:cleveland/1820-united-states-census] Before 1830, enumerators lacked pre-printed forms, and drew up their own, sometimes resulting in pages without headings, line tallies, or column totals.
[src:cleveland/1820-united-states-census] As a result, census records for many towns before 1830 are idiosyncratic.
[src:cleveland/1820-united-states-census] This is not to suggest that they are less reliable than subsequent censuses, but that they may require more work on the part of the researcher.
[src:cleveland/1830-united-states-census] The **1830 United States census**, the fifth census undertaken in the United States, was conducted on June 1, 1830.
[src:cleveland/1830-united-states-census] The only loss of census records for 1830 involved some countywide losses in Massachusetts, Maryland, and Mississippi.
[src:cleveland/1830-united-states-census] It determined the population of the 24 states to be 12,866,020, of which 2,009,043 were slaves.
[src:cleveland/1830-united-states-census] The center of population was about 170 miles (274 km) west of Washington, D.C. in present-day Grant County, West Virginia.
[src:cleveland/1830-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a city—New York—recorded a population of over 200,000.
[src:cleveland/1830-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1830 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:cleveland/1840-united-states-census] The **1840 United States census** was the sixth census of the United States.
[src:cleveland/1840-united-states-census] Conducted by U.S. marshals on June 1, 1840, it determined the resident population of the United States to be 17,069,453 – an increase of 32.7 percent over the 12,866,020 persons enumerated during the 1830 census.
[src:cleveland/1840-united-states-census] The total population included 2,487,355 slaves.
[src:cleveland/1840-united-states-census] In 1840, the center of population was about 260 miles (418 km) west of Washington, D.C., near Weston, Virginia (now in West Virginia).
[src:cleveland/1840-united-states-census] This was the last census conducted by U.S. marshals, as starting in 1850 a temporary office would be set up for each census under the purview of the Department of the Interior.
[src:cleveland/1840-united-states-census] This was due to the Northern members of the Whig Party opposing the controversial claim in the 1840 census that free Black Americans in the Northern United States suffered from a higher degree of "insane" or "idiotic" behavior compared to enslaved Black Americans.
[src:cleveland/1840-united-states-census] The 1840 census was the first that attempted to count Americans who were "insane" or "idiotic".
[src:cleveland/1840-united-states-census] Published results of the census indicated that alarming numbers of black persons living in non-slaveholding States were mentally ill, in striking contrast to the corresponding figures for slaveholding States.
[src:cleveland/1840-united-states-census] Pro-slavery advocates trumpeted the results as evidence of the beneficial effects of slavery, and the probable consequences of emancipation.
[src:cleveland/1840-united-states-census] The memorial was submitted to the House of Representatives by John Quincy Adams, who contended that it demonstrated "a multitude of gross and important errors" in the published returns.
[src:cleveland/1840-united-states-census] In response to the House's request for an inquiry, Secretary of State John C.
[src:cleveland/1840-united-states-census] Calhoun reported that a careful examination of the statistics by the supervisor of the census had fully sustained their correctness.
[src:cleveland/1840-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1840 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:cleveland/1840-united-states-census] A compendium of data from the sixth census, organized by States, counties, and principal towns is available on the web site of the Census Bureau.
[src:cleveland/1850-united-states-census] The **1850 United States census** was the seventh decennial United States Census Conducted by the Census Office, it determined the resident population of the United States to be 23,191,876—an increase of 35.9 percent over the 17,069,453 persons enumerated during the 1840 census.
[src:cleveland/1850-united-states-census] The total population included 3,204,313 enslaved people.
[src:cleveland/1850-united-states-census] Although the official date of the census date was June 1, 1850, completed census forms indicate that the surveys continued to be made throughout the rest of the year.
[src:cleveland/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census where there was an attempt to collect information about every member of every household and not only the head of the household.
[src:cleveland/1850-united-states-census] Slaves were included by gender and estimated age on Slave Schedules, listed by the name of the owner.
[src:cleveland/1850-united-states-census] Prior to 1850, census records had recorded only the name of the head of the household and broad statistical accounting of other household members (three children under age five, one woman between the age of 35 and 40, etc.).
[src:cleveland/1850-united-states-census] This was also the first census to ask about place of birth of free residents.
[src:cleveland/1850-united-states-census] Hinton Rowan Helper made extensive use of the 1850 census results in his influential anti-slavery book *The Impending Crisis of the South* (1857).
[src:cleveland/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census in which the US recorded a greater population than the United Kingdom (a year later) which it broke off from 65 years prior.
[src:cleveland/1850-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1850 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:cleveland/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census collected a great amount of data that gave insight into the state of the U.S. economy in 1850.
[src:cleveland/1850-united-states-census] Some of the data revealed the growth of the economy with regard to agricultural and manufactured production, international trade, federal debt, taxation, transportation, education, and land expansion.
[src:cleveland/1850-united-states-census] This census calculated the total land by state (in square miles), the total production of major goods and livestock per state (in respective units), the total value of each good produced, the total number of plantations per state, and various other statistics.
[src:cleveland/1850-united-states-census] The total agricultural production between in 1850 was calculated at about 1.3 billion dollars.
[src:cleveland/1850-united-states-census] Total manufactured production was valued at just over one billion dollars.
[src:cleveland/1850-united-states-census] This is a great increase over the totals estimated in 1820 and 1840.
[src:cleveland/1850-united-states-census] Also, in total, the manufacturing industry recorded an overall profit of 43%.
[src:cleveland/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census contains the total value of imports and exports by state, statistics and names of the major imports and exports, the total values of shipping by state, and the value of imports and exports with various individual countries.
[src:cleveland/1850-united-states-census] The United States traded most with the United Kingdom.
[src:cleveland/1850-united-states-census] The imports and exports with the United Kingdom were both valued around 145 million dollars.
[src:cleveland/1850-united-states-census] This census contains yearly federal debt totals, total federal revenues, and total expenditures from 1790 to 1853.
[src:cleveland/1850-united-states-census] The total debt of the United States on July 1, 1854, was roughly 47.2 million dollars.
[src:cleveland/1850-united-states-census] The census contains some calculation of total annual federal taxes, but it is incomplete.
[src:cleveland/1850-united-states-census] It does however, give state taxation totals.
[src:cleveland/1850-united-states-census] This census calculates the total cost, size, and quantity of railroads and canals.
[src:cleveland/1850-united-states-census] The funded debt for railroads and canals in 1853 was 130 million.
[src:cleveland/1850-united-states-census] Their gross earnings were more than 38 million dollars.
[src:cleveland/1850-united-states-census] This census also contains estimates for growth in mileage of telegraphic lines in the United States.
[src:cleveland/1850-united-states-census] of telegraphic lines, a drastic increase.
[src:cleveland/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census shows the great amount of territorial expansion that took place in the United States, following the Admission of Texas, the Oregon Treaty, and the Treaty with Mexico following the war in 1848.
[src:cleveland/1850-united-states-census] These three pieces of territory totaled an addition of more than a million square miles to the nation.
[src:cleveland/1850-united-states-census] In 1850, the United States contained 31 states and 4 organized territories (Minnesota, New Mexico, Oregon, Utah).
[src:cleveland/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census can be seen as a historical document that gives insight into the state of the nation's economy in 1850.
[src:cleveland/1850-united-states-census] It is much more detailed and provides more information than the 1840 census.
[src:cleveland/1850-united-states-census] This census was conducted during a very important period of growth and innovation in the United States, the Industrial Revolution.
[src:cleveland/1850-united-states-census] The statistics in this census provide data on the rate of growth that was taking place in 1850, which resulted in the emergence of the United States as an economic world power.
[src:cleveland/1850-united-states-census] Many of the statistics were compared to those of Great Britain and other world powers.
[src:cleveland/1850-united-states-census] This shows where the United States stood economically relative to the rest of the world.
[src:cleveland/1850-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1850 population census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:cleveland/1850-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:cleveland/1850-united-states-census] The Utah Territorial census was taken in 1851.
[src:cleveland/1850-united-states-census] Secretary Broughton Harris refused to certify the census of Utah Territory.
[src:cleveland/1850-united-states-census] Harris complained that Brigham Young had conducted the census without him, claimed several irregularities, and consequently withheld funds reserved for the census.
[src:cleveland/1850-united-states-census] The controversy contributed to Harris' decision to join other Runaway Officials of 1851 and abandon his post in Utah Territory.
[src:cleveland/1850-united-states-census] Relationships with the federal government continued to sour and eventually resulted in the Utah War.
[src:cleveland/1850-united-states-census] Local government officials feared having an enslaved population might impede the territory's quest for statehood, since certain members of Congress were concerned about expansion of slavery into the western territories.
[src:cleveland/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census slave schedule for Utah Territory reported only 26 slaves, with a note that all of them were heading to California, and did not include any enslaved people remaining in the territory.
[src:cleveland/1850-united-states-census] John David Smith estimates that there were 100 blacks in Utah by 1850, with two-thirds of them enslaved.
[src:cleveland/1860-united-states-census] The **1860 United States census** was the eighth census conducted in the United States, starting June 1, 1860, and lasting five months.
[src:cleveland/1860-united-states-census] It determined the population of the United States to be 31,443,321 in 33 states and 10 organized territories.
[src:cleveland/1860-united-states-census] This was an increase of 35.6 percent over the 23,191,876 persons enumerated during the 1850 census.
[src:cleveland/1860-united-states-census] The total population included 3,953,760 slaves.
[src:cleveland/1860-united-states-census] By the time the 1860 census returns were ready for tabulation, the nation was sinking into the American Civil War.
[src:cleveland/1860-united-states-census] As a result, census superintendent Joseph C.
[src:cleveland/1860-united-states-census] Kennedy and his staff produced only an abbreviated set of public reports, without graphic or cartographic representations.
[src:cleveland/1860-united-states-census] The statistics did allow the census staff to produce a cartographic display, including preparing maps of Southern states, for Union field commanders.
[src:cleveland/1860-united-states-census] These maps displayed militarily vital topics, including the white population, slave population, predominant agricultural products (by county), and rail and post road transportation routes.
[src:cleveland/1860-united-states-census] Philadelphia would lose its position as the second-most-populous American city to Chicago in 1890.
[src:cleveland/1860-united-states-census] The 1860 census Schedule 1 (Free Inhabitants) was one of two schedules that counted the population of the United States; the other was Schedule 2 (Slave Inhabitants).
[src:cleveland/1860-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1860 population census, including microdata, census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series (IPUMS).
[src:cleveland/1860-united-states-census] National data reveals that farmers (owners and tenants) made up nearly 10% of utilized occupations.
[src:cleveland/1860-united-states-census] Farm laborers (wage workers) represent the next highest percent with 3.2%, followed by general laborers at 3.0%.
[src:cleveland/1860-united-states-census] More localized data shows that other occupations were common.
[src:cleveland/1860-united-states-census] In the town of Essex, Massachusetts, a large section of the women in the labor force were devoted to shoe-binding, while for men the common occupations were farming and shoe-making.
[src:cleveland/1860-united-states-census] This heavy demand of shoe-related labor reinforces the high demand for rigorous physical laborers in the economy, as supported by the data of very large amounts of farm related work as compared to most other labor options.
[src:cleveland/1860-united-states-census] IPUMS' data also notes that the share of the population that had been enrolled in school or marked as "Student" stood at 0.2%.
[src:cleveland/1860-united-states-census] This demonstrates a small rate of growth, if any, in the proficiency of the human capital of the time—the skill set a worker has to apply to the labor force, which can increase total output through increased efficiency.
[src:cleveland/1860-united-states-census] The census of 1860 was the last in which much of Southern wealth was held as slaves—still legally considered property.
[src:cleveland/1870-united-states-census] The **1870 United States census** was the ninth United States census.
[src:cleveland/1870-united-states-census] It was conducted by the Census Office from June 1, 1870, to August 23, 1871.
[src:cleveland/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census was the first census to provide detailed information on the African American population, only five years after the culmination of the Civil War when slaves were granted freedom.
[src:cleveland/1870-united-states-census] The total population was 38,925,598 with a resident population of 38,558,371 individuals, a 22.6% increase from 1860.
[src:cleveland/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census's population estimate was controversial, as many believed it underestimated the true population numbers, especially in New York and Pennsylvania.
[src:cleveland/1870-united-states-census] This was the first census in which all 100 largest cities recorded populations of over 10,000.
[src:cleveland/1870-united-states-census] This was also the last federal census conducted using the US Marshal Service as enumerators.
[src:cleveland/1870-united-states-census] The Census Act of 1850 established the primary machinery of the ninth census.
[src:cleveland/1870-united-states-census] The Census Office, working within the Department of the Interior, oversaw the recording and tabulation of results gathered by assistant marshals, who were hired and supervised by federal marshals.
[src:cleveland/1870-united-states-census] Two new structural changes during the 1870 census occurred: marshals had to return the completed population questionnaire to the Census Office in September, and penalties for refusing to reply to enumerator questions were extended to encompass every question on the questionnaires.
[src:cleveland/1870-united-states-census] The commonly past-used slave questionnaires were redesigned to reflect the American society after the Civil War.
[src:cleveland/1870-united-states-census] The five schedules for the 1870 census were the following: General Population, Mortality, Agriculture, Products of Industry, and Social Statistics.
[src:cleveland/1870-united-states-census] The general population saw a 22.6% increase to 38,555,983 individuals in 1870.
[src:cleveland/1870-united-states-census] Charges of an undercount, however, were brought against Francis Amasa Walker, the Superintendent of the 1870 census.
[src:cleveland/1870-united-states-census] Mortality rates in 1870, in general, decreased as a fraction of the total population by <0.1% from 1860 and by 0.1% from 1850.
[src:cleveland/1870-united-states-census] The lower death rates indicate that the standard of living increased, due to some exogenous factor, over the period of twenty years from 1850 to 1870.
[src:cleveland/1870-united-states-census] In terms of products of industry, total U.S. wealth increased by 17.3% from 1860 to 1870, to reach an assessed wealth of $14,178,986,732.
[src:cleveland/1870-united-states-census] The four largest state contributors to this wealth were New York, Massachusetts, Pennsylvania, and Ohio, in that order.
[src:cleveland/1870-united-states-census] Most of the wealth was concentrated in the developed Northeast region, as newer territories like Wyoming were beginning to develop their young economies.
[src:cleveland/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census was the first of its kind to record the nativity of the American population.
[src:cleveland/1870-united-states-census] This social statistic helped determine which areas were more highly composed of immigrants than native-born Americans.
[src:cleveland/1870-united-states-census] New York City had the most foreign-born individuals, with 419,094 foreigners, who comprised 44.5% of the city's total population.
[src:cleveland/1870-united-states-census] Louis, and San Francisco also had a great population of foreigners that made up a significant fraction of their total populations.
[src:cleveland/1870-united-states-census] Therefore, a great ethnic and cultural change was witnessed from 1860 to 1870, as part of the population growth was due to immigrants moving in and a shuffling of residents across state borders.
[src:cleveland/1870-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1870 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:cleveland/1870-united-states-census] With especially bitter complaints coming from New York and Philadelphia claiming up to a third of the population was not counted, the President made the rare move to order a recount in those areas.
[src:cleveland/1870-united-states-census] While it was thought a large fraction of the population was not counted for being indoors in the wintry cold, newer estimates resulted in only a 2.5% increase in Philadelphia's population and a 2% increase in New York's.
[src:cleveland/1870-united-states-census] This controversy of the 1870 undercount resurfaced in 1890, when the national growth rate between 1880 and 1890 was discovered to be much lower than it was between 1870 and 1880.
[src:cleveland/1870-united-states-census] Critics then asserted that the 1870 population must have been underenumerated by over 1.2 million people to account for the discrepancy between growth rates; it was presumed that the growth rate in 1880 had to be exaggerated because of the 1870 undercount.
[src:cleveland/1870-united-states-census] Despite the fact that modern investigations have yet to quantify the exact effect of the undercount, most modern social scientists do not believe the undercount was as severe as 1890 investigators assumed.
[src:cleveland/1870-united-states-census] Today most analyzers compare the 1870 undercount to the non-response rates seen in most modern census data.
[src:cleveland/1880-united-states-census] The **1880 United States census**, conducted by the Census Office during June 1880, was the tenth United States census.
[src:cleveland/1880-united-states-census] It was the first time that women were permitted to be enumerators.
[src:cleveland/1880-united-states-census] The Superintendent of the Census was Francis Amasa Walker.
[src:cleveland/1880-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a city—New York City—recorded a population of over one million, and the first census in which the 20 most populated cities all recorded over 100,000 residents.
[src:cleveland/1880-united-states-census] Schedule 4 (Social statistics) was the responsibility of experts and special agents, rather than the enumerators.
[src:cleveland/1880-united-states-census] The majority of the data came from correspondence with officials of institutions providing care and treatment of certain members of the population.
[src:cleveland/1880-united-states-census] Experts and special agents also were employed to collect data on valuation, taxation, and indebtedness; religion and libraries; colleges, academies, and schools; newspapers and periodicals, and wages.
[src:cleveland/1880-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1880 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series, which contains microdata.
[src:cleveland/1880-united-states-census] The original census enumeration sheets were microfilmed by the Census Bureau; after which the original sheets were transferred to various state archives, libraries, or universities.
[src:cleveland/1880-united-states-census] The microfilmed census is available in rolls from the National Archives and Records Administration.
[src:cleveland/1880-united-states-census] Several organizations also host images of the microfilmed census online, along which digital indices.
[src:cleveland/1880-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1880 population census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:cleveland/1880-united-states-census] The 1880 census determined the resident population of the United States to be 50,189,209, an increase of 30.2 percent over the 38,555,983 persons enumerated during the 1870 census.
[src:cleveland/1880-united-states-census] The mean center of United States population for 1880 was in Boone County, Kentucky.
[src:cleveland/1880-united-states-census] The results from the census were used to determine the apportionment for the 48th, 49th, 50th, 51st, and 52nd sessions of the United States Congress.
[src:cleveland/1880-united-states-census] The processing of the 1880 census data took so long (eight years) that the Census Bureau contracted Herman Hollerith to design and build a tabulating machine to be used for the next census.
[src:cleveland/1880-united-states-census] The 1880 census also led to the discovery of the Alabama paradox.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Cleveland was founded in 1796 near the mouth of the Cuyahoga River as part of the Connecticut Western Reserve in modern-day Northeast Ohio by General Moses Cleaveland, after whom the city was named.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The city's location on the river and the lake shore allowed it to grow into a major commercial and industrial metropolis by the late 19th century, attracting large numbers of immigrants and migrants.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] It was among the top 10 largest U.S. cities by population for much of the 20th century, a period that saw the development of the city's cultural institutions.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] By the 1960s, Cleveland's economy began to slow down as manufacturing declined and suburbanization occurred.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Cleveland is a port city, connected to the Atlantic Ocean via the St.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Its economy relies on diverse sectors that include higher education, manufacturing, financial services, healthcare, and biomedicals.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The city serves as the headquarters of the Federal Reserve Bank of Cleveland, as well as several major companies.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The GDP for Greater Cleveland was US$138.3 billion in 2022.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Combined with the Akron metropolitan area, the eight-county Cleveland–Akron metropolitan economy was $176 billion in 2022, the largest in Ohio.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Known as "The Forest City" among many other nicknames, Cleveland serves as the center of the Cleveland Metroparks nature reserve system.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The city's major league professional sports teams include the Cleveland Browns (football; NFL), the Cleveland Cavaliers (basketball; NBA), and the Cleveland Guardians (baseball; MLB).
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Cleveland was established on July 22, 1796, by surveyors of the Connecticut Land Company when they laid out Connecticut's Western Reserve into townships and a capital city.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] They named the settlement "Cleaveland" after their leader, General Moses Cleaveland, a veteran of the American Revolutionary War.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Cleaveland oversaw the New England–style design of the plan for what would become the modern downtown area, centered on Public Square.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The town's name was often shortened to "Cleveland", including by Cleaveland's original surveyors.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] A myth emerged that the spelling was altered by *The Cleveland Advertiser* to fit the name on the newspaper's masthead.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The first permanent European settler in Cleveland was Lorenzo Carter, who arrived in May 1797 and built a cabin on the banks of the Cuyahoga River.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The emerging community served as an important supply post for the U.S. during the Battle of Lake Erie in the War of 1812.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Largely through the efforts of the settlement's first lawyer, Alfred Kelley, the village of Cleveland was incorporated on December 23, 1814.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Despite the nearby swampy lowlands and harsh winters, the town's waterfront on Lake Erie was advantageous, giving it access to Great Lakes trade.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] It grew rapidly after the 1832 completion of the Ohio and Erie Canal, which linked the Ohio River and the Great Lakes to the Atlantic Ocean via the Erie Canal and Hudson River, and later via the Saint Lawrence Seaway.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The town's growth continued with added railroad links.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] In 1836, Cleveland, then only on the eastern banks of the Cuyahoga, was incorporated as a city; John W.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The neighboring municipality of Ohio City was a major rival to Cleveland until its annexation by the city in 1854.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] A center of abolitionist activity, Cleveland (code-named "Station Hope") was a major stop on the Underground Railroad for escaped African American slaves en route to Canada.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The city served as an important center for the Union during the American Civil War, creating a large manufacturing industry within the city and unprecedented growth.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Its geographic location as a transportation hub on the Great Lakes contributed to its development as an industrial and commercial center.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Rockefeller founded Standard Oil in Cleveland; in 1885, he moved its headquarters to New York City.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Cleveland's economic growth and industrial jobs attracted large waves of immigrants from Southern Europe, Eastern Europe, and Ireland.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Urban growth was accompanied by labor unrest as workers demanded better wages and working conditions.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The Cleveland Streetcar Strike of 1899 was one of the more violent instances of labor strife in the city during this period.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] By 1910, Cleveland had become known as the "Sixth City" due to its status at the time as the sixth-largest U.S. city.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Its automotive companies included Peerless, Chandler, and Winton, maker of the first car driven across the U.S.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Other manufacturing industries in Cleveland included steam cars produced by White and electric cars produced by Baker.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Euclid Avenue became known as "Millionaires' Row" for its prestige and elegance.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Major Progressive Era politicians were leaders in the city, including populist Mayor Tom L.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Johnson, who was responsible for the development of the Cleveland Mall Plan.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The era of the City Beautiful movement in Cleveland architecture saw wealthy patrons support the establishment of the city's major cultural institutions including the Cleveland Museum of Art, which opened in 1916, and the Cleveland Orchestra, established in 1918.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] African American migrants from the rural South arrived in Cleveland as part of the Great Migration for jobs, constitutional rights, and relief from racial discrimination.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] By 1920 Cleveland had grown into a densely populated metropolis of 796,841, making it the fifth-largest city in the nation, with a foreign-born population of 30%.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Radical labor movements gained popularity in the city, such as the Industrial Workers of the World (IWW), in response to the conditions of the largely immigrant and migrant workers.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] In 1919, local socialist and IWW demonstrators clashed with anti-socialists in the May Day Riots, which occurred amid the First Red Scare and the strike wave that swept the U.S. that year.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Cleveland's population grew throughout the Roaring Twenties.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The decade saw the establishment of the city's Playhouse Square, and the rise of the risqué Short Vincent.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The Bal-Masque balls of the avant-garde Kokoon Arts Club scandalized the city.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Jazz came to prominence in Cleveland during this period.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Prohibition was established in Ohio in May 1919 (although it was not well-enforced in Cleveland), became law with the Volstead Act in 1920, and was repealed nationally by Congress in 1933.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The ban on alcohol led to the rise of speakeasies throughout the city and organized crime gangs, such as the Mayfield Road Mob, who smuggled bootleg liquor across Lake Erie from Canada into Cleveland.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] In 1929, Cleveland hosted the first of many National Air Races, and Amelia Earhart flew to the city from Santa Monica, California in the Women's Air Derby.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The Van Sweringen brothers commenced construction of the Terminal Tower skyscraper in 1926 and oversaw its completion in 1927.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] When the building was dedicated as part of Cleveland Union Terminal in 1930, the city had a population of over 900,000.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Cleveland's economy was greatly effected by the Wall Street Crash of 1929 and Great Depression.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] A center of union activity, the city saw significant labor struggles in this period, including strikes by workers against Fisher Body in 1936 and against Republic Steel in 1937.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The city was aided by major federal works projects sponsored by President Franklin D.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] In commemoration of the centennial of Cleveland's incorporation as a city, the Great Lakes Exposition debuted in June 1936 at the city's North Coast Harbor, along the Lake Erie shore north of downtown.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Conceived by Cleveland's business leaders as a way to revitalize the city during the Depression, it drew four million visitors in its first season, and seven million by the end of its second and final season in September 1937.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] During World War II, Cleveland was a major hub of the U.S. war effort as the fifth largest manufacturing center in the nation.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] During the war the city established the Cleveland Transit System, the predecessor to the Greater Cleveland Regional Transit Authority.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Cleveland experienced an economic boom after the war and businesses declared the city to be the "best location in the nation".
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The decade saw the rising popularity of the rock and roll music genre.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] By the 1960s, Cleveland's economy slowed and residents sought new housing in the suburbs, reflecting national trends of suburban growth following federally subsidized highways.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Industrial restructuring, particularly in the steel and automotive industries, resulted in the loss of numerous jobs in Cleveland and the city suffered economically.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The burning of the Cuyahoga River in June 1969 brought national attention to the issue of industrial pollution in Cleveland and catalyzed the American environmental movement.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Housing discrimination and redlining against African Americans led to racial unrest in Cleveland; the Hough riots erupted from July 18 to 24, 1966, and the Glenville Shootout took place on July 23, 1968.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] In November 1967, Cleveland became the first major American city to elect an African American mayor, Carl B.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Stokes, who worked to restore the Cuyahoga River.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] During the 1970s, Cleveland was known as "Bomb City U.S.A." due to several bombings that shook the city, mostly due to organized crime rivalries.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] In December 1978, Cleveland became the first major American city since the Great Depression to enter a financial default on federal loans.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The national recession of the early 1980s eroded the city's traditional economic industries; Cleveland's unemployment rate of 13.8% was higher than the national average due to the closure of several steel production centers.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The city began an economic recovery in the 1980s.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Although the city emerged from default in 1987, it suffered from the impact of the subprime mortgage crisis and the Great Recession.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] By the 21st century, Cleveland had developed a more diversified economy and gained a national reputation as a center for healthcare and the arts.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The city's downtown and several neighborhoods experienced significant population growth since 2010, while overall population decline has slowed.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The city has a total area of 82.47 square miles (213.6 km2), of which 77.70 square miles (201.2 km2) is land and 4.77 square miles (12.4 km2) is water.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The shore of Lake Erie is 569 feet (173 m) above sea level; the city lies on a series of irregular bluffs lying roughly parallel to the lake.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] In Cleveland, these bluffs are cut principally by the Cuyahoga River, Big Creek, and Euclid Creek.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The land rises quickly from the lake shore elevation of 569 feet.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Public Square, less than one mile (1.6 km) inland, sits at an elevation of 650 feet (198 m), and Hopkins Airport, five miles (8.0 km) inland from the lake, is at an elevation of 791 feet (241 m).
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Cleveland borders several inner-ring and streetcar suburbs.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] To the west, it borders Lakewood, Rocky River, and Fairview Park, and to the east, it borders Shaker Heights, Cleveland Heights, South Euclid, and East Cleveland.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] To the southwest, it borders Linndale, Brooklyn, Parma, and Brook Park.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] To the south, the city borders Newburgh Heights, Cuyahoga Heights, and Brooklyn Heights and to the southeast, it borders Warrensville Heights, Maple Heights, and Garfield Heights.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] To the northeast, along the shore of Lake Erie, Cleveland borders Bratenahl and Euclid.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Many of the city's government and civic buildings, including City Hall, the Cuyahoga County Courthouse, the Cleveland Public Library, and Public Auditorium, are clustered around the open Cleveland Mall and share a common neoclassical architecture.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] They were built in the early 20th century as the result of the 1903 Group Plan.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] They constitute one of the most complete examples of City Beautiful design.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Completed in 1927 and dedicated in 1930 as part of the Cleveland Union Terminal complex, the Terminal Tower is a prototypical Beaux-Arts skyscraper.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] It was the tallest building in North America outside New York City until 1964 and the tallest in the city until 1991.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Key Tower (the tallest building in Ohio) and 200 Public Square combine elements of Art Deco architecture with postmodern designs.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Nicknamed Cleveland's "Crystal Palace", the five-story Cleveland Arcade (also known as the Old Arcade) was built in 1890 and renovated in 2001 as a Hyatt Regency Hotel.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The Cleveland Trust Company Building was completed in 1907 and renovated in 2015 as a downtown Heinen's supermarket.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Cleveland's historic ecclesiastical architecture includes the Presbyterian Old Stone Church, the onion-domed St.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Theodosius Russian Orthodox Cathedral, and the Roman Catholic Cathedral of St.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] John the Evangelist along with several other ethnically inspired Catholic churches.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The Cleveland City Planning Commission has designated 34 neighborhoods in Cleveland.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Centered on Public Square, Downtown Cleveland is the city's central business district, encompassing subdistricts such as the Nine-Twelve District, the Campus District, the Civic Center, East 4th Street, Playhouse Square, and the Short Vincent entertainment district.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Mixed-use areas, such as the Warehouse District and the Superior Arts District, are occupied by industrial and office buildings as well as restaurants, cafes, and bars.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The number of condominiums, lofts, and apartments has been on the increase since 2000 and especially 2010, reflecting downtown's growing population.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Clevelanders geographically define themselves by whether they live on the east or west side of the Cuyahoga River.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The East Side includes the neighborhoods of Buckeye–Shaker, Buckeye–Woodhill, Central, Collinwood (including Nottingham), Euclid–Green, Fairfax, Glenville, Goodrich–Kirtland Park (including Asiatown), Hough, Kinsman, Lee–Miles (including Lee–Harvard and Lee–Seville), Mount Pleasant, St.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Clair–Superior, Union–Miles Park, and University Circle (including Little Italy).
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The Cuyahoga Valley neighborhood (including Whiskey Island and the Flats) is situated between the East and West Sides, while Broadway–Slavic Village is sometimes referred to as the South Side.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Several neighborhoods have seen the return of the middle class that left the city for the suburbs in the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] These include Ohio City, Tremont, Detroit–Shoreway, and Edgewater on the West Side, and Collinwood, Hough, Fairfax, and Little Italy on the East Side.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The growth was spurred by attracting creative class members, which has facilitated new residential development and the transformation of old industrial buildings into loft spaces for artists.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Cleveland exhibits a humid continental (Köppen: *Dfa*) or humid subtropical (Köppen: *Cfa*) climate, depending on the isotherm used.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Due to its proximity to Lake Erie, Cleveland experiences milder temperatures than much of Ohio, with relatively cooler summers and warmer winters.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] East of the mouth of the Cuyahoga, the land elevation rises rapidly in the south.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Together with the prevailing winds off Lake Erie, this feature is the principal contributor to the lake-effect snow that is typical in Cleveland (especially on the city's East Side) from mid-November until the surface of the lake freezes, usually in late January or early February.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The lake effect causes a relative differential in geographical snowfall totals across the city.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] On the city's far West Side, the Hopkins neighborhood only reached 100 inches (254 cm) of snowfall in a season three times since record-keeping for snow began in 1893.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] By contrast, seasonal totals approaching or exceeding 100 inches (254 cm) are not uncommon as the city ascends into the Heights on the east, where the region known as the "Snow Belt" begins.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Extending from the city's East Side and its suburbs, the Snow Belt reaches up the Lake Erie shore as far as Buffalo.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The all-time record high in Cleveland of 104 °F (40 °C) was established on June 25, 1988, and the all-time record low of −20 °F (−29 °C) was set on January 19, 1994.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] On average, July is the warmest month with a mean temperature of 74.5 °F (23.6 °C), and January, with a mean temperature of 29.1 °F (−1.6 °C), is the coldest.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Normal yearly precipitation based on the 30-year average from 1991 to 2020 is 41.03 inches (1,042 mm).
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The least precipitation occurs on the western side and directly along the lake, and the most occurs in the eastern suburbs.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Parts of Geauga County to the east receive over 44 inches (1,100 mm) of liquid precipitation annually.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] With its extensive cleanup of its Lake Erie shore and the Cuyahoga River, Cleveland has been recognized by national media as an environmental success story and a national leader in environmental protection.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Since the city's industrialization, the Cuyahoga River had become so affected by industrial pollution that it "caught fire" a total of 13 times beginning in 1868.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] It was the river fire of June 1969 that spurred the city to action under Mayor Carl B.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Stokes, and played a key role in the passage of the Clean Water Act in 1972 and the National Environmental Policy Act later that year.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Since that time, the Cuyahoga has been extensively cleaned up through the efforts of the city and the Ohio Environmental Protection Agency (OEPA).
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] In addition to continued efforts to improve freshwater and air quality, Cleveland is now exploring renewable energy.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The city's two main electrical utilities are FirstEnergy and Cleveland Public Power.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Its climate action plan, updated in December 2018, has a 2050 target of 100% renewable power, along with reduction of greenhouse gases to 80% below the 2010 level.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] In recent decades, Cleveland has been working to address the issue of harmful algal blooms on Lake Erie, fed primarily by agricultural runoff, which have presented new environmental challenges for the city and for northern Ohio.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Cleveland has seen a population decline over the past century.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The city's population was 914,808 according to the 1950 Census.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] According to the 2020 census, there were 372,624 people and 170,549 households in Cleveland.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The population density was 4,901.51 inhabitants per square mile (1,892.5/km2).
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The median household income was $30,907 and the per capita income was $21,223.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] 32.7% of the population was living below the poverty line.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Of the city's population over the age of 25, 17.5% held a bachelor's degree or higher, and 80.8% had a high school diploma or equivalent.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] As of 2020, the racial and ethnic composition of the city was 47.5% African American, 32.1% non-Hispanic white, 13.1% Hispanic or Latino, 2.8% Asian, 0.2% Native American, and 3.8% from two or more races.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] 85.3% of Clevelanders age five and older spoke only English at home, while 14.7% spoke a language other than English, including Spanish, Arabic, Chinese, Hungarian, Albanian, and various Slavic languages (Russian, Polish, Serbian, Croatian, and Slovene).
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The city's spoken accent is an advanced form of Inland Northern American English, similar to other Great Lakes cities, but distinctive from the rest of Ohio.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] , now serves an African American congregation.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] In the 19th and early 20th centuries, Cleveland saw a massive influx of immigrants from Ireland, Italy, and the Austro-Hungarian, German, Russian, and Ottoman empires, most of whom were attracted by manufacturing jobs.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The presence of Hungarians within Cleveland proper was, at one time, so great that the city boasted the highest concentration of Hungarians in the world outside of Budapest.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Cleveland has a long-established Jewish community, historically centered on the East Side neighborhoods of Glenville and Kinsman, but now mostly concentrated in East Side suburbs such as Cleveland Heights and Beachwood, location of the Maltz Museum of Jewish Heritage.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The availability of jobs attracted African Americans from the South.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Between 1910 and 1970, the black population of Cleveland, largely concentrated on the city's East Side, increased significantly as a result of the First and Second Great Migrations.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Cleveland's Latino community consists primarily of Puerto Ricans, as well as smaller numbers of immigrants from Mexico, Cuba, the Dominican Republic, South and Central America, and Spain.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The city's Asian community, centered on historical Asiatown, consists of Chinese, Koreans, Vietnamese, and other groups.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Additionally, the city and the county have significant communities of Albanians, Arabs (especially Lebanese, Syrians, and Palestinians), Armenians, French, Greeks, Iranians, Scots, Turks, and West Indians.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] A 2020 analysis found Cleveland to be the most ethnically and racially diverse major city in Ohio.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The influx of immigrants in the 19th and early 20th centuries drastically transformed Cleveland's religious landscape.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] From a homogeneous settlement of New England Protestants, it evolved into a city with a diverse religious composition.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The predominant faith among Clevelanders today is Christianity, with Jewish, Muslim, Hindu, and Buddhist minorities.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Within Cleveland, the neighborhoods with the highest foreign-born populations are Asiatown/Goodrich–Kirtland Park (32.7%), Clark–Fulton (26.7%), West Boulevard (18.5%), Brooklyn Centre (17.3%), Downtown (17.2%), University Circle (15.9%, with 20% in Little Italy), and Jefferson (14.3%).
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Recent waves of immigration have brought new groups to Cleveland, including Ethiopians and South Asians, as well as immigrants from Russia and the former USSR, Southeast Europe (especially Albania), the Middle East, East Asia, and Latin America.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] In the 2010s, the immigrant population of Cleveland and Cuyahoga County began to see significant growth.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] A 2019 study found Cleveland to be the city with the shortest average processing time in the nation for immigrants to become U.S. citizens.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The city's annual One World Day in Rockefeller Park includes a naturalization ceremony of new immigrants.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Cleveland's location on the Cuyahoga River and Lake Erie has been key to its growth as a major commercial center.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Steel and many other manufactured goods emerged as leading industries.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The city has since diversified its economy in addition to its manufacturing sector.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Established in 1914, the Federal Reserve Bank of Cleveland is one of 12 U.S.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Its downtown building, located on East 6th Street and Superior Avenue, was completed in 1923 by the Cleveland architectural firm Walker and Weeks.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The headquarters of the Federal Reserve System's Fourth District, the bank employs 1,000 people and maintains branch offices in Cincinnati and Pittsburgh.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Cleveland and Cuyahoga County are home to *Fortune 500* companies Cleveland-Cliffs, Progressive, Sherwin-Williams, Parker-Hannifin, KeyCorp, and Travel Centers of America.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] NASA maintains the Glenn Research Center in Cleveland.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Jones Day, one of the largest law firms in the U.S., was founded in Cleveland in 1893.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Healthcare plays a major role in Cleveland's economy.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The city's "Big Three" hospital systems are the Cleveland Clinic, University Hospitals, and MetroHealth.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The Cleveland Clinic is the largest private employer in the state of Ohio, with a workforce of over 55,000 as of 2022.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] It carries the distinction of being one of the best hospital systems in the world.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The clinic is led by Croatian-born president and CEO Tomislav Mihaljevic and it is affiliated with Case Western Reserve University School of Medicine.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] University Hospitals includes the University Hospitals Cleveland Medical Center and its Rainbow Babies & Children's Hospital.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Cliff Megerian serves as that system's CEO.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] MetroHealth on the city's west side is led by president and CEO Christine Alexander-Rager.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Formerly known as City Hospital, it operates one of two Level I trauma centers in the city, and has various locations throughout Greater Cleveland.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] In 2013, Cleveland's Global Center for Health Innovation opened with 235,000 square feet (21,800 m2) of display space for healthcare companies across the world.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] To take advantage of the proximity of universities and other medical centers in Cleveland, the Veterans Administration moved the region's VA hospital from suburban Brecksville to a new facility in University Circle.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Cleveland's Playhouse Square is the second largest performing arts center in the U.S. behind New York City's Lincoln Center.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] It includes the State, Palace, Allen, Hanna, and Ohio theaters.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The theaters host Broadway musicals, special concerts, speaking engagements, and other events throughout the year.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Playhouse Square's resident performing arts companies include Cleveland Ballet, the Cleveland International Film Festival, the Cleveland Play House, Cleveland State University Department of Theatre and Dance, DANCECleveland, the Great Lakes Theater Festival, and the Tri-C Jazz Fest.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] A city with strong traditions in theater and vaudeville, Cleveland has produced many renowned performers, most prominently comedian Bob Hope.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Outside Playhouse Square is Karamu House, the oldest African American theater in the nation, established in 1915.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] On the West Side, the Gordon Square Arts District in the Detroit–Shoreway neighborhood is the location of the Capitol Theatre, the Near West Theatre, and an Off-Off-Broadway playhouse, the Cleveland Public Theatre.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The Dobama Theatre and the Beck Center for the Arts are based in Cleveland's streetcar suburbs of Cleveland Heights and Lakewood respectively.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The Cleveland Orchestra is widely considered one of the world's finest orchestras, and often referred to as the finest in the nation.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] It is one of the "Big Five" major orchestras in the U.S.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The orchestra plays at Severance Hall in University Circle during the winter and at Blossom Music Center in Cuyahoga Falls during the summer.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] One Playhouse Square, now the headquarters for Cleveland's public broadcasters, was initially used as the broadcast studios of WJW (AM), where disc jockey Alan Freed first popularized the term "rock and roll".
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Beginning in the 1950s, Cleveland gained a strong reputation as a key breakout market for rock music.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Its popularity in the city was so great that Billy Bass, the program director at the WMMS radio station, referred to Cleveland as "The Rock and Roll Capital of the World".
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The Cleveland Agora Theatre and Ballroom has served as a major venue for rock concerts in the city since the 1960s.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] From 1974 through 1980, the city hosted the World Series of Rock at Cleveland Municipal Stadium.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Jazz and R&B have a long history in Cleveland.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Many major figures in jazz performed in the city, including Louis Armstrong, Cab Calloway, Duke Ellington, Ella Fitzgerald, Dizzy Gillespie, and Billie Holiday.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Legendary pianist Art Tatum regularly played in Cleveland clubs in the 1930s, and gypsy jazz guitarist Django Reinhardt gave his U.S. debut performance in Cleveland in 1946.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Prominent jazz artist Noble Sissle was a graduate of Cleveland Central High School, and Artie Shaw worked and performed in Cleveland early in his career.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The Tri-C Jazz Fest has been held annually in Cleveland at Playhouse Square since 1980, and the Cleveland Jazz Orchestra was established in 1984.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The city has a history of polka music being popular both past and present and is the location of the Polka Hall of Fame.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] A subgenre called Cleveland-style polka, named after the city.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The music's popularity is due in part to the success of Frankie Yankovic, a Cleveland native who was considered "America's Polka King".
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The first film shot in Cleveland was in 1897 by the company of Ohioan Thomas Edison.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Before Hollywood became the center for American cinema, filmmaker Samuel Brodsky and playwright Robert McLaughlin operated a film studio at the Andrews mansion on Euclid Avenue (now the WEWS-TV studio).
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] There they produced major silent-era features, such as *Dangerous Toys* (1921), which are now considered lost.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Brodsky also directed the weekly *Plain Dealer Screen Magazine* that ran in theaters in Cleveland and Ohio from 1917 to 1924.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] In addition, Cleveland hosted over a dozen sponsored film studios, including Cinécraft Productions, which still operates in Ohio City.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] In the "talkie" era, Cleveland featured in several major studio films, such as Michael Curtiz's pre-Code classic *Goodbye Again* (1933) with Warren William and Joan Blondell.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Players from the 1948 Cleveland Indians appeared in *The Kid from Cleveland* (1949).
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Billy Wilder's *The Fortune Cookie* (1966) was set and filmed in the city and marked the first onscreen pairing of Walter Matthau and Jack Lemmon.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Labor struggles in Cleveland were depicted in *Native Land* (1942), narrated by Paul Robeson, and in Norman Jewison's *F.I.S.T.* (1978) with Sylvester Stallone.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Clevelander Jim Jarmusch's *Stranger Than Paradise* (1984) – a deadpan comedy about two New Yorkers who travel to Florida by way of Cleveland – was a favorite of the Cannes Film Festival.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] *Major League* (1989) reflected the perennial struggles of the Cleveland Indians, while *American Splendor* (2003) reflected the life of Cleveland graphic novelist Harvey Pekar.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] *Kill the Irishman* (2011) depicted the 1970s turf war between Danny Greene and the Cleveland crime family.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Cleveland has doubled for other locations in films.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The wedding and reception scenes in *The Deer Hunter* (1978), while set in suburban Pittsburgh, were shot in Cleveland's Tremont neighborhood.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] *A Christmas Story* (1983) was set in Indiana, but drew many external shots from Cleveland.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The opening shots of *Air Force One* (1997) were filmed in and above Severance Hall, and *Judas and the Black Messiah* (2021) was filmed in Cleveland, although set in Chicago.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Downtown Cleveland doubled for Manhattan in *Spider-Man 3* (2007), *The Avengers* (2012), and *The Fate of the Furious* (2017), and for Metropolis in James Gunn's *Superman* (2025).
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Future productions are handled by the Greater Cleveland Film Commission at the Leader Building on Superior Avenue.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] In television, the city is the setting for the popular network sitcom *The Drew Carey Show*, starring Cleveland native Drew Carey.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] *Hot in Cleveland*, a comedy that aired on TV Land, premiered on June 16, 2010, and ran for six seasons until its finale on June 3, 2015.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] *Cleveland Hustles*, the CNBC reality show co-created by LeBron James, was filmed in the city.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Cleveland has a thriving literary and poetry community, with regular poetry readings at bookstores, coffee shops, and various other venues.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] In 1925, Russian Futurist poet Vladimir Mayakovsky came to Cleveland and gave a poetry recitation to the city's ethnic working class, as part of his trip to America.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The Cleveland State University Poetry Center serves as an academic center for poetry in the city.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Langston Hughes, preeminent poet of the Harlem Renaissance and child of an itinerant couple, lived in Cleveland as a teenager and attended Central High School in Cleveland in the 1910s.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] At Central High, the young writer was taught by Helen Maria Chesnutt, daughter of Cleveland-born African American novelist Charles W.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Hughes authored some of his earliest poems, plays, and short stories in Cleveland and contributed to the school newspaper.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The African American avant-garde poet Russell Atkins lived in the city as well.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The American modernist poet Hart Crane was born in nearby Garrettsville, Ohio in 1899.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] His adolescence was divided between Cleveland and Akron before he moved to New York City in 1916.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Cleveland was the home of Joe Shuster and Jerry Siegel, who created the comic book character Superman in 1933.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Harlan Ellison, noted author of speculative fiction, was born in Cleveland in 1934.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] As a young man, he published a series of short stories appearing in the *Cleveland News*, and performed in a number of productions for the Cleveland Play House.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Cleveland is the site of the Anisfield-Wolf Book Award, which recognizes books that have contributed to the understanding of racism and human diversity.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Presented by the Cleveland Foundation, it remains the only American book prize focusing on works that address racism and diversity.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The Cleveland Museum of Art is a major American art museum, with a collection that includes more than 60,000 works of art.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The Museum of Contemporary Art Cleveland showcases established and emerging artists, particularly from the Cleveland area, through hosting and producing temporary exhibitions.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Both museums offer free admission to visitors.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The two museums are part of Cleveland's University Circle, a 550-acre (2.2 km2) concentration of cultural, educational, and medical institutions located 5 miles (8.0 km) east of downtown.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] In addition to the art museums, the neighborhood includes the Cleveland Botanical Garden, Case Western Reserve University, University Hospitals, Severance Hall, the Maltz Performing Arts Center, the Cleveland Museum of Natural History, and the Western Reserve Historical Society.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Also located at University Circle is the Cleveland Cinematheque at the Cleveland Institute of Art.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Pei-designed Rock and Roll Hall of Fame is located on Cleveland's Lake Erie waterfront at North Coast Harbor downtown.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Neighboring attractions include Cleveland Browns Stadium, the Great Lakes Science Center, the Steamship Mather Museum, the International Women's Air & Space Museum, and the USS *Cod*, a World War II submarine.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Scofield, the Soldiers' and Sailors' Monument at Public Square is Cleveland's major Civil War memorial and a major attraction in the city.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Other city attractions include Grays Armory, the Cleveland Masonic Temple, and the Children's Museum of Cleveland.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] A Cleveland holiday attraction, especially for fans of Jean Shepherd's *A Christmas Story*, is the Christmas Story House and Museum in Tremont.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Cleveland hosts the WinterLand holiday display lighting festival annually at Public Square.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The Cleveland International Film Festival has been held in the city since 1977, and the Cleveland Silent Film Festival has been held since 2022.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The Cleveland National Air Show, an indirect successor to the National Air Races, has been held at the city's Burke Lakefront Airport since 1964.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The Great Lakes Burning River Fest, a two-night music and beer festival at Whiskey Island, has been sponsored by the Great Lakes Brewing Company since 2001.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Many ethnic festivals are held in Cleveland throughout the year.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] These include the annual Feast of the Assumption in Little Italy, Russian Maslenitsa in Rockefeller Park, the Puerto Rican Parade and Cultural Festival in Clark–Fulton, the Cleveland Asian Festival in Asiatown, the Tremont Greek Fest, and the St.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Cleveland also hosts annual Polish Dyngus Day and Slovene Kurentovanje celebrations.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The city's annual Saint Patrick's Day parade brings hundreds of thousands to the streets of Downtown.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] The Cleveland Thyagaraja Festival held each spring at Cleveland State University is the largest Indian classical music and dance festival in the world outside of India.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Since 1946, the city has annually marked One World Day in the Cleveland Cultural Gardens in Rockefeller Park, celebrating all of its ethnic communities.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Cleveland's mosaic of ethnic communities and their various culinary traditions have long played an important role in defining the city's cuisine.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Local mainstays include an abundance of Slavic, Hungarian, and Central-Eastern European contributions, such as kielbasa, stuffed cabbage, pierogies, goulash, and chicken paprikash.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Italian, German, Irish, and Jewish cuisines are also prominent in Cleveland, as are Lebanese, Greek, Chinese, Puerto Rican, Mexican, and numerous other ethnic cuisines.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Vendors at the West Side Market in Ohio City offer many ethnic foods for sale.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] In addition, the city boasts a vibrant barbecue and soul food scene.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Slyman's Deli on Cleveland's near East Side is notable for its corned beef sandwich, with patrons including former U.S.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Another celebrated sandwich, the Polish Boy, is a popular street food and Cleveland original frequently sold at downtown hot dog carts and stadium concession stands.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Brown stadium mustard is synonymous with Cleveland, especially Bertman Original Ballpark Mustard.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Another notable local food item with Depression-era roots is city chicken.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] With its blue-collar roots well intact, and plenty of Lake Erie perch and walleye available, the tradition of Friday night fish fries remains alive and thriving in Cleveland, particularly in ethnic parish-based settings, especially during the season of Lent.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Clambakes are likewise embedded into the city's culinary culture.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] For dessert, the Cleveland Cassata Cake is a unique treat invented in the local Italian community and served in Italian establishments throughout the city.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Another popular dessert, the locally crafted Russian Tea Biscuit, is common in many Jewish bakeries in Cleveland.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Cleveland is noted in the world of celebrity food culture.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Famous local figures include chef Michael Symon and food writer Michael Ruhlman, both of whom achieved local and national attention for their contributions to the culinary world.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] In 2007, Symon helped gain the spotlight when he was named "The Next Iron Chef" on the Food Network.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] That same year, Ruhlman collaborated with Anthony Bourdain, to do an episode of his *Anthony Bourdain: No Reservations* focusing on Cleveland's restaurant scene.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Ohio produces the fifth most beer in the U.S., with its largest brewery being Cleveland's Great Lakes Brewing Company.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Cleveland has had a long history of brewing, tied to many of its ethnic immigrants, and has reemerged as a regional leader in production.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Dozens of breweries exist within city limits, including large producers such as Market Garden Brewery.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Although breweries can be found throughout the city, the highest concentration is in the Ohio City neighborhood.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p01] Cleveland hosts expansions from other countries as well, including the Scottish BrewDog and German Hofbrauhaus.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Cleveland's major professional sports teams are the Cleveland Guardians (Major League Baseball), the Cleveland Browns (National Football League), and the Cleveland Cavaliers (National Basketball Association).
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Other professional teams include the Cleveland Monsters (American Hockey League), the Cleveland Charge (NBA G League), the Cleveland Crunch (Major League Indoor Soccer), Cleveland SC (National Premier Soccer League), and the Cleveland Fusion (Women's Football Alliance).
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Local sporting venues include Progressive Field, Huntington Bank Field, Rocket Arena, the Wolstein Center, and Public Auditorium.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] The Cleveland Guardians – known as the Indians from 1915 to 2021 – won the World Series in 1920 and 1948.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] They also won the American League pennant, making the World Series in the 1954, 1995, 1997, and 2016 seasons.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Between 1995 and 2001, the team sold out 455 consecutive games, a Major League Baseball record that stood until 2008.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Historically, the Browns have been among the most successful franchises in American football history, winning eight titles during a short period of time – 1946, 1947, 1948, 1949, 1950, 1954, 1955, and 1964.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] The Browns have never played in a Super Bowl, getting close five times by making it to the NFL/AFC Championship Game in 1968, 1969, 1986, 1987, and 1989.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Former owner Art Modell's relocation of the Browns after the 1995 season caused tremendous heartbreak and resentment among local fans.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] After a series of lawsuits, a compromise was reached between Modell, Cleveland mayor Michael R.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] White, and NFL and Commissioner Paul Tagliabue to bring back the Browns beginning in the 1999 season, retaining all team history.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] In Cleveland's earlier football history, the Cleveland Bulldogs won the NFL Championship in 1924, and the Cleveland Rams won the NFL Championship in 1945 before relocating to Los Angeles.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] The Cavaliers won the Eastern Conference in 2007, 2015, 2016, 2017 and 2018 but were defeated in the NBA Finals by the San Antonio Spurs and then by the Golden State Warriors, respectively.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] The Cavs won the Conference again in 2016 and won their first NBA Championship coming back from a 3–1 deficit, finally defeating the Golden State Warriors.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Afterwards, over 1.3 million people attended a parade held in the Cavs' honor on June 22, 2016, in downtown Cleveland.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Previously, the Cleveland Rosenblums dominated the original American Basketball League, and the Cleveland Pipers, owned by George Steinbrenner, won the American Basketball League championship in 1962.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] The Cleveland Monsters of the American Hockey League won the 2016 Calder Cup.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] They were the first Cleveland AHL team to do so since the 1964 Barons.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Collegiately, NCAA Division I Cleveland State Vikings have 19 varsity sports, nationally known for their Cleveland State Vikings men's basketball team.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] NCAA Division III Case Western Reserve Spartans have 17 varsity sports, most known for their Case Western Reserve Spartans football team.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] The headquarters of the Mid-American Conference (MAC) are in Cleveland.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] The conference stages both its men's and women's basketball tournaments at Rocket Arena.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] The Cleveland Marathon has been hosted annually since 1978, and a monument commemorating one of Cleveland's most prominent track and field athletes, Jesse Owens, stands at the city's Fort Huntington Park.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] The second American Chess Congress, a predecessor to the U.S.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Championship, was held in Cleveland in 1871, and won by George Henry Mackenzie.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Open Chess Championships took place in the city, and were won by Edward Lasker and Bobby Fischer, respectively.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] In 2014, Cleveland hosted the ninth official Gay Games ceremony.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] In July 2024, the city hosted the Pan American Masters Games.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Known locally as the "Emerald Necklace", the Olmsted-inspired Cleveland Metroparks encircle Cleveland and Cuyahoga County.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] The city proper encompasses the Metroparks' Brookside and Lakefront Reservations, as well as significant parts of the Rocky River, Washington, and Euclid Creek Reservations.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] The Lakefront Reservation, which provides public access to Lake Erie, consists of four parks: Edgewater Park, Whiskey Island–Wendy Park, East 55th Street Marina, and Gordon Park.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Three more parks fall under the jurisdiction of the Euclid Creek Reservation: Euclid Beach, Villa Angela, and Wildwood Marina.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Further south, bike and hiking trails in the Brecksville and Bedford Reservations, along with Garfield Park, provide access to trails in the Cuyahoga Valley National Park.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Also included in the Metroparks system is the Cleveland Metroparks Zoo, established in 1882.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Located in Big Creek Valley, the zoo has one of the largest collections of primates in North America.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] In addition to the Metroparks, the Cleveland Public Parks District oversees the city's neighborhood parks, the largest of which is the historic Rockefeller Park.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] The latter is notable for its late 19th century landmark bridges, the Rockefeller Park Greenhouse, and the Cleveland Cultural Gardens, which celebrate the city's ethnic diversity.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Just outside of Rockefeller Park, the Cleveland Botanical Garden in University Circle, established in 1930, is the oldest civic garden center in the nation.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] In addition, the Greater Cleveland Aquarium, located in the historic FirstEnergy Powerhouse in the Flats, is the only independent, free-standing aquarium in the state of Ohio.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Cleveland operates on a mayor–council (strong mayor) form of government, in which the mayor is the chief executive and the city council serves as the legislative branch.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] City council members are elected from 15 wards to four-year terms.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] From 1924 to 1931, the city briefly experimented with a council–manager government under William R.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Morgan before returning to the mayor–council system.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Cleveland is served by Cleveland Municipal Court, the first municipal court in the state.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] District Court for the Northern District of Ohio, based at the Carl B.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] The Chief Judge for the Northern District is Sara Elizabeth Lioi and the Clerk of Court is Sandy Opacich.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] The office of the mayor has been held by Justin Bibb since 2022.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Previous mayors include progressive Democrat Tom L.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Johnson, World War I-era War Secretary and BakerHostetler founder Newton D.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Supreme Court Justice Harold Hitz Burton, two-term Ohio Governor and Senator Frank J.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Health, Education, and Welfare Secretary Anthony J.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Celebrezze, two-term Ohio Governor and Senator George Voinovich, former U.S.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Congressman Dennis Kucinich, and Carl B.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Stokes, the first African American mayor of a major U.S. city.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Jackson was the city's longest-serving mayor.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] The President of Cleveland City Council is Blaine Griffin, the council Majority Leader is Jasmin Santana, and the Majority Whip is Charles Slife.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Patricia Britt serves as the Clerk of Council.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Historically, from the Civil War era to the 1940s, Cleveland had been dominated by the Republican Party, with the notable exceptions of the Johnson and Baker mayoral administrations.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Businessman and Senator Mark Hanna was among Cleveland's most influential Republican figures, both locally and nationally.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Another nationally prominent Ohio Republican, former U.S.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Garfield, was born in Cuyahoga County's Orange Township (today the Cleveland suburb of Moreland Hills).
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Garfield Memorial in Cleveland's Lake View Cemetery.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Today Cleveland is a major stronghold for the Democratic Party in Ohio.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Although local elections are nonpartisan, Democrats still dominate every level of government.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Politically, Cleveland and several of its neighboring suburbs comprise Ohio's 11th congressional district.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] The district is represented by Shontel Brown, one of five Democrats representing the state of Ohio in the U.S.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Cleveland has hosted three Republican national conventions, in 1924, 1936, and 2016.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Additionally, the city hosted the 1864 Radical Democratic National Convention.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Although Cleveland has not hosted a national convention for the Democrats, it has hosted several national election debates, including the second 1980 U.S. presidential debate, the 2004 U.S. vice presidential debate, one 2008 Democratic primary debate, and the first 2020 U.S. presidential debate.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Founded in 1912, the City Club of Cleveland provides a platform for national and local debates and discussions.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Known as Cleveland's "Citadel of Free Speech", it is one of the oldest continuous independent free speech and debate forums in the country.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] The current Safety Director for the city of Cleveland is Dornat "Wayne" Drummond.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Like in other major American cities, crime in Cleveland is concentrated in areas with higher rates of poverty and lower access to jobs.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] In recent decades, the rate of crime in the city, although higher than the national average, experienced a significant decline, following a nationwide trend in falling crime rates.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] However, as in other major U.S. cities, crime in Cleveland saw an abrupt rise in 2020–21.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Cleveland's law enforcement agency is the Cleveland Division of Police, established in 1866.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] The division had roughly 1,100 sworn officers as of 2024, covering five police districts.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] The district system was introduced in the 1930s by Cleveland Public Safety Director Eliot Ness (of the Untouchables), who later ran for mayor of Cleveland in 1947.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] In addition, the Cuyahoga County Sheriff's Office is based in Downtown Cleveland at the Justice Center Complex.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Cleveland is served by the firefighters of the Cleveland Division of Fire, established in 1863.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] The fire department operates out of 22 active fire stations throughout the city in five battalions.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Each Battalion is commanded by a Battalion Chief, who reports to an on-duty Assistant Chief.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] The Division of Fire operates a fire apparatus fleet of twenty-two engine companies, eight ladder companies, three tower companies, two task force rescue squad companies, hazardous materials ("haz-mat") unit, and numerous other special, support, and reserve units.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] The interim Chief of Department is Wayne Naida.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Cleveland EMS is operated by the city as its own municipal third-service EMS division.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Cleveland EMS is the primary provider of Advanced Life Support and ambulance transport within the city of Cleveland, while Cleveland Fire assists by providing fire response medical care.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Although a merger between the fire and EMS departments was proposed in the past, the idea was subsequently abandoned.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] The EMS Commissioner is Orlando Wheeler.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Cleveland serves as headquarters to Coast Guard District 9 and is responsible for all U.S.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Coast Guard operations on the five Great Lakes, the Saint Lawrence Seaway, and surrounding states accumulating 6,700 miles of shoreline and 1,500 miles of international shoreline with Canada.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Station Cleveland Harbor, located in North Coast Harbor, has a responsibility covering about 550 square miles of the federally navigable waters of Lake Erie, including the Cuyahoga and Rocky rivers, as well as a number of their tributaries.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Cleveland is served by the Cleveland Metropolitan School District.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] It is the only K–12 district in Ohio under the direct control of the mayor, who appoints a school board.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Approximately 1 square mile (2.6 km2) of Cleveland's Buckeye–Shaker neighborhood is part of the Shaker Heights City School District.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] The area, which has been a part of the Shaker school district since the 1920s, permits these Cleveland residents to pay the same school taxes as the Shaker residents, as well as vote in the Shaker school board elections.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] There are several private and parochial schools in Cleveland.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] These include Benedictine High School, Cleveland Central Catholic High School, Eleanor Gerson School, St.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Cleveland is home to a number of colleges and universities.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Most prominent among them is Case Western Reserve University (CWRU), a widely recognized research and teaching institution based in University Circle with several major graduate programs.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] University Circle also contains the Cleveland Institute of Art and the Cleveland Institute of Music.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Downtown Cleveland is home to Cleveland State University, a public research university with eight constituent colleges, and the metropolitan campus of Cuyahoga Community College.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Ohio Technical College is also based in Cleveland.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Cleveland's suburban universities and colleges include Baldwin Wallace University in Berea, John Carroll University in University Heights, and Ursuline College in Pepper Pike.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Established in 1869, the Cleveland Public Library is one of the largest public libraries in the nation with a collection of over 13 million materials in 2023.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] It holds the Northeast Ohio Broadcast Archives, and the John G.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] White Special Collection, with the largest chess library in the world and a rare collection of folklore and books on the Middle East and Eurasia.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] The library's main building was designed by Walker and Weeks and dedicated in 1925, under head librarian Linda Eastman, the first woman to lead a major library system in the U.S.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Between 1904 and 1920, 15 libraries built with funds from Andrew Carnegie were opened in the city.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Known as the "People's University", the library presently maintains 27 branches.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] It serves as the headquarters for the CLEVNET library consortium, which includes 47 public library systems in Northeast Ohio.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Cleveland's primary daily newspaper is *The Plain Dealer* and its associated online publication, *Cleveland.com*.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Defunct major newspapers include the *Cleveland Press* and the *Cleveland News*.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Additional publications include *Cleveland Magazine*, a regional culture magazine published monthly; *Crain's Cleveland Business*, a weekly business newspaper; and *Cleveland Scene*, a free alternative weekly paper which absorbed its competitor, the *Cleveland Free Times*, in 2008.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] The digital *Belt Magazine* was founded in Cleveland in 2013.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] *Time* magazine was published in Cleveland from 1925 to 1927.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Several ethnic publications are based in Cleveland.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] The Cleveland-area television market is served by 11 full power stations, including WKYC (NBC), WEWS-TV (ABC), WJW (Fox), WDLI-TV (Bounce), WOIO (CBS), WVPX-TV (Ion), WVIZ (PBS), WUAB (MyNetworkTV), WRLM (TCT), WBNX-TV (CW), and WQHS-DT (Univision).
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] As of 2021, the market, which includes the Akron and Canton areas, was the 19th-largest in the country, as measured by Nielsen Media Research.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Cleveland is directly served by 29 full power AM and FM radio stations, 21 of which are licensed to the city.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] WMMS also serves as the FM flagship for the Cleveland Cavaliers and the Cleveland Guardians, WNCX is an FM flagship for the Cleveland Browns, and WJMO is the Spanish flagship for the Browns and Cavaliers.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] News/talk stations include WHK, WTAM, and WERE.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] During the Golden Age of Radio, WHK was the first radio station to broadcast in Ohio, and one of the first in the country.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] WTAM is the AM flagship for both the Cleveland Cavaliers and the Cleveland Guardians.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Sports stations include WKNR (ESPN), WARF (Fox/VSiN) and WKRK-FM (WW1), with WKNR and WKRK-FM serving as co-flagship stations for the Cleveland Browns, and WARF – though primarily an English language station – airing Spanish broadcasts of Cleveland Guardians home games.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Religious stations include WHKW, WCCR, and WCRF.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] As the regional NPR affiliate, WKSU serves all of Northeast Ohio (including both the Cleveland and Akron markets).
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] College stations include WBWC (Baldwin Wallace), WJCU (John Carroll), and WRUW-FM (Case Western Reserve).
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Cleveland has a bus and rail mass transit system operated by the Greater Cleveland Regional Transit Authority (RTA).
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] The rail portion is officially called the RTA Rapid Transit, but local residents refer to it as *The Rapid*.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] It consists of three light rail lines, known as the Blue, Green, and Waterfront Lines, and a heavy rail line, the Red Line.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] In 2008, RTA completed the HealthLine, a bus rapid transit line, for which naming rights were purchased by the Cleveland Clinic and University Hospitals.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] It runs along Euclid Avenue from downtown through University Circle, ending at the Louis Stokes Station at Windermere in East Cleveland.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] In 1968, Cleveland became the first city in the nation to have a direct rail transit connection linking the city's downtown to its major airport.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] In 2021, Walk Score ranked Cleveland the 17th most walkable of the 50 largest cities in the U.S., with a Walk Score of 57, a Transit Score of 45, and a Bike Score of 55 (out of a maximum of 100).
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Cleveland's most walkable areas can be found in the Downtown, Ohio City, Detroit–Shoreway, University Circle, and Buckeye–Shaker neighborhoods.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Like other major cities, the urban density of Cleveland reduces the need for private vehicle ownership.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] In 2016, 23.7% of Cleveland households lacked a car, while the national average was 8.7%.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Cleveland averaged 1.19 cars per household in 2016, compared to a national average of 1.8.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Cleveland's road system consists of numbered streets running roughly north–south, and named avenues, which run roughly east–west.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] The numbered streets are designated "east" or "west", depending on where they lie in relation to Ontario Street, which bisects Public Square.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] The two downtown avenues which span the Cuyahoga change names on the west side of the river.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Superior Avenue becomes Detroit Avenue on the West Side, and Carnegie Avenue becomes Lorain Avenue.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] The bridges that make these connections are the Hope Memorial (Lorain–Carnegie) Bridge and the Veterans Memorial (Detroit–Superior) Bridge.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Cleveland is served by three two-digit interstate highways – I-71, I-77, and I-90 – and by two three-digit interstates – I-480 and I-490.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Running due east–west through the West Side suburbs, I-90 turns northeast at the junction with I-490, and is known as the Cleveland Inner Belt.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] The Cleveland Memorial Shoreway carries SR 2 along its length, and at varying points carries US 6, US 20 and I-90.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] At the junction with the Shoreway, I-90 makes a 90-degree turn in the area known as Dead Man's Curve, then continues northeast.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] The Jennings Freeway (SR 176) connects I-71 just south of I-90 to I-480.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] A third highway, the Berea Freeway (SR 237 in part), connects I-71 to the airport and forms part of the boundary between Brook Park and Cleveland's Hopkins neighborhood.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Cleveland is a major North American air market, serving 4.93 million people.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Cleveland Hopkins International Airport is the city's primary major airport and an international airport that serves the broader region.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Originally known as Cleveland Municipal Airport, it was the first municipally owned airport in the country.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Cleveland Hopkins is a significant regional air freight hub hosting FedEx Express, UPS Airlines, U.S.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Postal Service, and major commercial freight carriers.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] In addition to Hopkins, Cleveland is served by Burke Lakefront Airport, on the north shore of downtown between Lake Erie and the Shoreway.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Burke is primarily a commuter and business airport.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] The Port of Cleveland, at the Cuyahoga River's mouth, is a major bulk freight and container terminal on Lake Erie, receiving much of the raw materials used by the region's manufacturing industries.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] The Port of Cleveland is the only container port on the Great Lakes with bi-weekly container service between Cleveland and the Port of Antwerp in Belgium on a Dutch service called the Cleveland-Europe Express.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] In addition to freight, the Port of Cleveland welcomes regional and international tourists who pass through the city on Great Lakes cruises.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Cleveland has a long history as a major railroad hub in North America.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Today, Amtrak provides service to Cleveland, via the *Capitol Limited* and *Lake Shore Limited* routes, which stop at Cleveland Lakefront Station.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Additionally, Cleveland hosts several inter-modal freight railroad terminals, for Norfolk Southern, CSX and several smaller companies.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] National intercity bus service is provided by Greyhound from its downtown bus station.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Akron Metro, Brunswick Transit Alternative, Laketran, Lorain County Transit, and Medina County Transit provide connecting bus service to the Greater Cleveland Regional Transit Authority.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Geauga County Transit and Portage Area Regional Transportation Authority (PARTA) also offer connecting bus service in their neighboring areas.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Cleveland maintains cultural, economic, and educational ties with 27 sister cities around the world.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] It concluded its first sister city partnership with Lima, Peru, in 1964.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] In addition, Cleveland hosts the Consulate General of the Republic of Slovenia, which, until Slovene independence in 1991, served as an official consulate for Tito's Yugoslavia.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] The Cleveland Clinic operates the Cleveland Clinic Abu Dhabi hospital, two outpatient clinics in Toronto, and a hospital campus in London.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] The Cleveland Council on World Affairs was established in 1923.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Historically, Cleveland industrialist Cyrus S.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] Rockefeller, played a significant role in promoting dialogue between the U.S. and the Soviet Union during the Cold War.
[src:cleveland/cleveland-p02] In October 1915 at Cleveland's Bohemian National Hall, Czech American and Slovak American representatives signed the Cleveland Agreement, calling for the formation of a joint Czech and Slovak state.
